    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so once i have that impedance value, how do i find the total current in the circuit? also does the phase angle matter for anything specific here?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Once you have the impedance ($Z$), you can find the total current ($I$) using Ohm's Law for AC circuits: $I = V/Z$. Here, $V$ is the source voltage (12V AC) and $Z$ is the total impedance you just calculated. The phase angle is important because it tells you the phase relationship between the voltage and the current, which will be leading or lagging in an RL circuit. Since you have an inductor, the current will lag the voltage by that phase angle, $\\phi = \\arctan(X_L/R)$.",
      "source": "target",
